 of self and other through surprise encounters: James Baldwin sees himself in the face of Bette Davis, family resemblance is read in Richard S. Robert's portrait of an interracial family, and black film pioneer George P. Johnson looks back on Micheaux. Given the impossibility of purity and the co-implication of white and black, Fire and Desire ultimately questions the category of "race movies" itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican Americans in motion pictures. 0aRacially mixed people in motion pictures. 0aRacially mixed peoplezUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  afilm, silent, cinema, segregation, mixed-race, interracial, movies, race films, independent, birth of a nation, black filmmakers, oscar micheaux, within our gates, what happened in the tunnel, sexuality, desire, kiss, miscegenation, self, purity, george p johnson, family, richard s robert, resemblance, inheritance, bette davis, james baldwin, recognition, surprise, unexpected, nonfiction, biracial, embodiment, riot, belonging, inclusion, diversity, marginalized.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226278735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226278735/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles